observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to:
Follow the proper documentation in the grant and liquidation of cash advances per COA Circular No. 2012-001; 
Attach the Report of Disbursements for the cash advances made for the payment of salaries and other compensation benefits and the necessary supporting documents as mentioned above; 
Direct the Municipal Accountant to review and ensure that paid payrolls submitted by the Municipal Treasurer were complete in documentary requirements and were duly signed by the claimants and bearing signatures of the authorized approving officials before recording 100% liquidation in the JEV and finally forwarded to the COA Audit Team; and

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Direct the Bids and Awards Committee to:

Meticulously and judiciously plan the Municipality’s procurement process;

Regulate the LGU’s government procurements to ensure all are done through competitive bidding unless an alternative mode of procurement is practicable following the provisions of the Revised IRR of RA 9184; 

Ensure that the Annual Procurement Plan is properly prepared following the prescribed format by the GPPB indicating the proper mode of procurement and for any changes thereof, a BAC Resolution approved by the HoPe, shall be issued, and the APP shall be updated accordingly before pursuing another mode of procurement;

Furnish a copy of the PPMP and APP to the Office of the Auditor;

Strictly observe that no procurement shall be authorized and undertaken unless it is following the approved APP.

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the disbursement vouchers are supported with a copy of the APP showing the mode of procurement; and

Ensure adherence to the guidelines outlined in RA 9184 and its IRR throughout the procurement process of goods, services, and infrastructure projects to promote transparency, efficiency, and cost-effectiveness.

We recommended the following:

The General Service Office should fast-track the immediate transfer of ownership of all real properties acquired by the Municipality.

Records all acquired real properties in the Physical Inventory of property, plants, and equipment reports and furnishes copies to the COA Audit Team of the transferred title.

The Municipal Accountant should adhere to the documentary requirements in the purchase of land as follows:

Certificate of availability of funds;

Original copy of Deed of Sale approved and duly registered in the proper Register of Deeds or the decision of the Court, in the case of eminent domain;

A certificate of title duly entered in favor of the government or other evidence satisfactory to COA that title is in the government;

Recommendation of the Appraisal Committee as to the reasonableness of price, duly approved by the authorities concerned and noted by the previous owner; and

Copy of the latest tax declaration transferred from the owner-vendor to the government.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Create an Inventory Committee intended for the one-time cleansing, composed of an adequate number of members to complete the physical inventory in three months or less. The Inventory Committee shall have at least one member each from the Accounting and Property Divisions/Units of the agency;

Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct the one-time cleansing of the Municipality's PPE accounts following the prescribed procedures embodied in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;

Send an invitation to the Commission on Audit to witness the inventory taking;

After the conduct of inventory taking, ensure compliance with the following:

The Inventory Committee is to prepare and submit to the Audit Team in the prescribed format the Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) and the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) if there are unserviceable properties found during inventory taking; 

The GSO to update the property records based on the results of the physical inventory and reconcile with accounting records to come up with the reconciled balances of PPE accounts to be considered the correct balance of the Municipality's PPE; and 

The Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit the necessary adjusting entries on the deficiencies noted based on the result of the actual inventory taking and disclose in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive: 

Direct the MDRRM Officer to:

Prepare and submit the LDRRMFIP annually, presenting the current year appropriation – 30% allocation for QRF in lump-sum and the allocation for disaster mitigation, prevention, and preparedness with details as to projects and activities to be funded and under a separate caption the list of projects and activities charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years. The same should be updated annually;

Ensure that the release and use of the LDRRMF are supported by LDRRMFIP;

Ensure that all budgeted projects, programs, and activities outlined in the LDRRMFIP are solely to support disaster risk reduction and management activities and implemented accordingly in optimal and effective use for the benefit of its constituents; and

Require the Municipal Budget Officer to prepare and maintain separate Registries of Appropriations, Allotments, and Obligations (RAAOs) for the LDRRMF: (1) RAAO-for QRF, (2) RAAO-for MOOE, and (3) RAAO-for CO.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:

Direct the BAC or BAC Secretariat to:

Send written invitations or notices to the COA Office and at least two other qualified observers at least five (5) calendar days before the scheduled public biddings as required in the Revised IRR of RA 9184;

Submit the contracts and purchase orders together with the documentary requirements enumerated in the checklists for submission to the COA Audit Team for the auditorial and legal review within five (5) working days from execution of a contract or issuance of a purchase order, and ultimately to the COA Technical Audit Services depending on the amount involved;

Direct the General Supply Officer to furnish copies of Inspection and Acceptance Reports, together with the delivery receipts to the Audit Team within twenty-four hours from acceptance thereof; and

Direct the General Supply Officer (GSO)/ BAC Secretariat to strictly adhere to the provisions of the Revised IRR of RA 9184, COA Circular No. 96-010 dated August 15, 1996, COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 12, 2009, COA Circular No. 2009-002 dated May 18, 2009, and the Government Accounting Manual for LGUs.

We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Create an inventory committee headed by the GSO to conduct an actual physical inventory taking of all properties of the Municipality to establish the accuracy, existence, and completeness of the reported PPE in the financial statements;
Instruct the inventory committee thru the GSO that if no records could be found, start recording the actual existence of buildings, equipment, motor vehicles, furniture and fixtures by office, and if possible, reconstruct the records;
Direct the GSO to:
Assign property number for each PPE item;
Prepare a separate report on unserviceable properties and equipment and facilitate the preparation of Inspection and Inventory Report;
Update the property records based on the results of the physical inventory and reconcile with accounting records to come up with the reconciled balances of PPE accounts to be considered as the correct balance of the agency's PPE;
Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjustments on the deficiencies noted based on the result of the actual inventory taking;
Furnish the COA Audit Team with a copy of the Updated Inventory Report; and
Ensure strict adherence to the above-stated laws, rules, and regulations.

We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Require the Human Resource Management Officer to:
Furnish the accounting office with a copy of the schedule of earned leave credits of all LGU personnel with money value as the basis for its proper recognition and monitoring;
Allow special monetization of 50% or more leave credits only for valid and justifiable reasons, and resort to the use of sick leave credits only upon exhaustion of vacation leave credits pursuant to CSC Resolution 000034, and after obtaining the favorable recommendation of the LCE to support it.
Direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the accrued money equivalent to the earned leave credits of the LGU personnel, especially those who will be retiring in the succeeding year;
Gradually start setting up the Leave Benefits Payable account for the accrual of the money equivalent to the earned leave credits of the LGU personnel, provided there is enough budget for the purpose;
Ensure that all payments for monetization and terminal leave benefits were supported with complete documentary requirements, particularly that special monetization of 50% or more of the earned leave credits;
Direct the Human Resource Management Officer and Municipal Accountant to reconcile their records and ledger regularly; and
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to assess whether the amount of the annual appropriated budget for the Terminal Leave Benefits is sufficient to cover the employee benefits of the LGU personnel and make adjustments if necessary.

We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Ensure that the Municipal Budget is carefully prepared and reviewed so that the actual needs of the Municipality are properly appropriated and allocated in the budget;
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to:
Properly assign the account codes so as not to cause a disparity in the recording of the actual obligations and expenditures;
Regularly update the required registries to prevent the incurrence of expenditures in excess of appropriations and allotments. The expenditures should be limited to what was appropriated;
Make sure that the Obligation Request which is the basis for recording of obligations in the registries is properly accomplished to facilitate monitoring of expenses and balances of appropriations; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Budget Officer to coordinate with each other to determine the proper account to be used in recording the financial transactions.

We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Require the officials and employees to submit their duly signed daily time records (DTRs) and approved applications for leave (if any) in support of their claims indicated in the payroll;
Direct the Municipal Treasure to make sure the payroll was duly approved by the authorized officials by affixing their signatures before processing and releasing the funds, and require all claimants in the payroll to affix their signatures after receipt of cash;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to review and ensure that paid payrolls submitted by the Municipal Treasurer were complete in documentary requirements and were duly signed by the claimants and bearing signatures of the authorized officials before recording 100% liquidation in the JEV and finally forwarded to the COA Audit Team; and
Adopt the Automated Teller Machine (ATM) payroll system of an authorized government depository bank to minimize cash advances in the payment of salaries and wages of government officials and employees.

We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Direct the municipal officials/personnel to refrain from claiming reimbursements for fuel, oil and lubricants consumed using government motor vehicles if the same are receiving transportation allowance. Likewise, when using private vehicles for official travels, concerned officials or personnel can only claim equivalent fare with the corresponding certification;
Require all officials and personnel concerned to prepare properly accomplished driver’s trip tickets and pre-approved before undertaking the trip and a summary of which shall be made at the end of the month in a Monthly Report of Official Travels, for audit purposes;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that payments for fuel expenses are duly supported with properly filled out driver’s trip tickets for proper evaluation of the propriety and reasonableness of fuel consumption before recording the same in the books of accounts;
Direct the GSO to strengthen controls in the withdrawal and consumption of fuel to ensure expenditures pertaining thereto are not excessive and unnecessary and submit to the Commission on Audit, the Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption not later than ten (10) days of the succeeding month for validation; and
Urge all officials and employees to strictly comply with the provisions of COA Circular No. 77-61 to be properly guided in the documentation of fuel consumption and the use of government vehicles/equipment as well as to be able to regulate fuel consumption.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to: 

Create an inventory committee to conduct an actual physical inventory taking of all properties, plant and equipment headed by the General Services Officer;

Instruct the Committee thru the GSO that if no records could be found, start recording the actual existence of equipment, furniture and fixtures by office and if possible, reconstruct the records;

Require the GSO to maintain property cards for property, plant and equipment. Deliveries of property shall be immediately recorded in the property records on the basis of the AIR and other supporting documents;

Instruct the General Service Officer to provide property number of all properties, at the same time, maintain stock cards with the Municipal Accountant who will maintain a subsidiary ledger card;

Require the GSO to segregate the unserviceable properties and prepare an Inspection and Inventory Report for disposal;

Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare necessary adjustments on the deficiencies noted in the course of inventory taking and make reconciliation with inventory report, stock cards and subsidiary ledgers;

Require the General Services Officer to attend seminars related to property management; and

Strictly adhere to the above-stated rules and regulations.

